Charlecote, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Charlecote, Warw, Engl":"Charlecote, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","of Charlicote, Warwick or Norwich, Eng.":"Charlecote, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lucy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Lucey  .","French: habitational name from any of various places called Lucy, originally named with the Latin personal name <i>Lucius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lucey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Maeve, Niall.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luasaigh</b>, an altered form of <b>Mac Cluasaigh</b>, a Cork name meaning ‘son of <i>Cluasach</i>’, a byname originally denoting someone with large or otherwise noticeable ears (from <i>cluas</i> ‘ear’).","English: variant of   Luce   1."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Lucy was born about 1294, in Charlecote, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Lucy Knight about 1321, in Charlecote, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1294–":"umbes 1